SIMPLE: income
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Income
<hw>In"come</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A coming
in; entrance; admittance; ingress; infusion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>More abundant <qex>incomes</qex> of light and strength from
God.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Rust.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At mine <qex>income</qex> I louted low.</q>
<rj><qau>Drant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is caused to enter; inspiration;
influence; hence, courage or zeal imparted.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would then make in and steep⟦br⟧
My <qex>income</qex> in their blood.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That gain which proceeds from labor, business,
property, or capital of any kind, as the produce of a farm, the rent of
houses, the proceeds of professional business, the profits of commerce
or of occupation, or the interest of money or stock in funds, etc.;
revenue; receipts; salary; especially, the annual receipts of a private
person, or a corporation, from property; <as>as, a large
<ex>income</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No fields afford⟦br⟧
So large an <qex>income</qex> to the village lord.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>That which is taken into the
body as food; the ingesta; -- sometimes restricted to the nutritive, or
digestible, portion of the food. See <er>Food</er>. Opposed to
<ant>output</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Income bond</b></col>, <cd>a bond issued on the income of
the corporation or company issuing it, and the interest of which is to
be paid from the earnings of the company before any dividends are made
to stockholders; -- issued chiefly or exclusively by railroad
companies.</cd> -- <col><b>Income tax</b></col>, <cd>a tax upon a
person's incomes, emoluments, profits, etc., or upon the excess beyond a
certain amount.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Gain; profit; proceeds; salary; revenue;
receipts; interest; emolument; produce.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incomer</ent>⟦br⟧
